ictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Newton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Scottish: habitational name from any of the many places in England and Scotland so named, from Old English <i>nīwe</i> ‘new’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, settlement’, or Middle English <i>neue</i> ‘new’ + <i>toun</i> ‘settlement, town’. According to Ekwall, this is the commonest English placename. For this reason, the surname has a highly fragmented origin."],"variants":[{"name":"Newtown","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Albon.","English (Yorkshire): variant of   Newton  . This surname is now rare in Britain.","Americanized form (translation into English) of French   Villeneuve  ."]}]},{"name":"Isolde","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["The name of the tragic mistress of Tristan in the Arthurian romances. There are several versions of the story. The main features are that the beautiful Isolde, an Irish princess, is betrothed to the aged King Mark of Cornwall. However, through accidentally drinking a magic potion, she and the young Cornish knight Tristan fall in love, with tragic consequences. The story has exercised a powerful hold on the European imagination. The name was relatively common in Britain in the Middle Ages, but is much rarer today."],"variants":[{"name":"Isolda","meanings":["The name of the tragic mistress of Tristan in the Arthurian romances. There are several versions of the story. The main features are that the beautiful Isolde, an Irish princess, is betrothed to the aged King Mark of Cornwall. However, through accidentally drinking a magic potion, she and the young Cornish knight Tristan fall in love, with tragic consequences. The story has exercised a powerful hold on the European imagination. The name was relatively common in Britain in the Middle Ages, but is much rarer today."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Isolde de Newton was born in 1173, in Newton, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, William de Newton, was 26 and her mother, Alice of Vallefort, was 23. She had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with John De Weston, Magister."},"et":{"1173–":"1173–Surnud","1173–Female":"1173–Surnud","1169–1227":"1169–1227","1195–1258":"1195–1258","1205–Female":"1205–Surnud","1148–Male":"1148–Surnud","1151–Female":"1151–Surnud","1205":"1205","1227":"1227","1148":"1148","1258":"1258","1169":"1169","1173":"1173","1195":"1195","1151":"1151","Weston, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Weston, Staffordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Newton, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Newton, Staffordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Weston, Staffordshire, England":"Weston, Staffordshire, England"},"fi":{"1173–":"1173–Kuollut","1173–Female":"1173–Kuollut","1169–1227":"1169–1227","1195–1258":"1195–1258","1205–Female":"1205–Kuollut","1148–Male":"1148–Kuollut","1151–Female":"1151–Kuollut","1205":"1205","1227":"1227","1148":"1148","1258":"1258","1169":"1169","1173":"1173","1195":"1195","1151":"1151","Weston, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Weston, Staffordshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Newton, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Newton, Staffordshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Weston, Staffordshire, England":"